Now I can see the issue! Looking at the `CompletableFutureCoroutine` class, specifically the `onCancelled` method on lines 60-65, I can see the problematic code:

```kotlin
override fun onCancelled(cause: Throwable, handled: Boolean) {
    if (!future.completeExceptionally(cause) && !handled) {
        // prevents loss of exception that was not handled by parent & could not be set to CompletableFuture
        handleCoroutineException(context, cause)
    }
}
```

The issue here is that when `onCancelled` is called, it tries to complete the `CompletableFuture` with the exception using `future.completeExceptionally(cause)`. However, if the future was already completed (like when it was explicitly cancelled), this call returns `false`, and then the code calls `handleCoroutineException(context, cause)`, which triggers the global exception handler.

According to the issue description and the expected behavior, the `future` coroutine builder should only deliver errors via the returned `CompletableFuture`, just like `async` does. It should NOT trigger the global exception handler.

Let me also look at how `async` works to understand the expected behavior better. Let me find the async implementation:

